<DESCRIPT>  ARTS; SHOW; FREMONT  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Contemporary interpretations of ancient artifacts is the theme of the current
exhibit "Ancient Allegories" at the Olive Hyde Art Gallery. Three artists
create two- and three-dimensional works with textiles, sculpture, and
painting.;    Michael and Marlene Collins of Fremont collaborate on the
three-dimensional "Spirit Figures," which reflects the peoples of Africa,
Mexico, Egypt and the Native Americans from the northwest coast.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  The Weekly  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  NEW LOOK AT 'ANCIENT' THEME
WORKS FEATURED AT OLIVE HYDE GALLERY  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Joy Gladding, of Casto Valley, is an award-winning fiber artist. She
incorporates found objects on painted canvas in works such as "Apron: Dryland
1991.";    Sarah Fereguson of Huntington Beach recreates ancient petroglyphs
in a mixed-media format.;    The Olive Hyde gallery is located at 123
Washington Blvd., across from Mission San Jose in Fremont. Gallery hours are
12:30 to 5 p.m. Wednesdays through Sunday and from 6 p.m. to 8:30 p.m.
Thursday. "Ancient Allegories" runs through Aug. 18.  </TEXT>
